Paul: One of the coming
attractions

57:19.667 --> 57:21.908
that I think is gonna to have
the biggest impact

57:21.917 --> 57:25.660
is what is called
marine permaculture.

57:25.667 --> 57:28.124
It's just another way of
farming in the ocean,

57:28.125 --> 57:30.616
but this is a more wild farming

57:30.625 --> 57:32.786
because it actually
sets up the context

57:32.792 --> 57:35.750
for the oceans to
regenerate themselves.

57:45.292 --> 57:47.999
Paul: Dr Brian Von herzen,
a physicist,

57:48.000 --> 57:49.490
used to fly to Europe every year

57:49.500 --> 57:53.243
and he saw how quickly the
Greenland ice sheet was melting

57:53.250 --> 57:55.912
and decided to change
his whole life in 2006

57:55.917 --> 57:57.407
to restoring living systems,

57:57.417 --> 57:58.907
and focused on the ocean.

58:03.167 --> 58:05.533
Damon: Brian told me
to pack a lunch...

58:05.542 --> 58:07.498
And a sick bag,

58:07.500 --> 58:10.037
as we were spending the day
out at sea.

58:16.625 --> 58:18.536
Man: With 93% of global warming

58:18.542 --> 58:20.533
going into the ocean today
each year,

58:20.542 --> 58:23.499
the problem is that
the waters are getting too warm

58:23.500 --> 58:25.912
and without enough
overturning circulation,

58:25.917 --> 58:27.498
and there aren't enough
nutrients,

58:27.500 --> 58:30.412
and the result is
we lose the life in the ocean.

58:32.125 --> 58:34.912
Damon: Understandably,
there has been reluctance

58:34.917 --> 58:36.657
to meddle with our oceans.

58:37.917 --> 58:39.657
But the fact that they
are getting warmer,

58:39.667 --> 58:41.749
becoming acidic,

58:41.750 --> 58:45.288
and many fish species are now
in danger of collapse...

58:47.125 --> 58:49.286
Means that they
actually need our help.

58:52.417 --> 58:55.033
Brian's solution is seaweed.

58:56.917 --> 58:59.408
So what we do
with marine permaculture

58:59.417 --> 59:02.614
is we restore
overturning circulation.

59:02.625 --> 59:05.742
It's as if your leg was asleep
and you lost circulation.

59:05.750 --> 59:07.411
We have to do that
with the ocean.

59:07.417 --> 59:09.908
We've gotta get that
overturning circulation

59:09.917 --> 59:10.906
going again

59:10.917 --> 59:13.874
to bring the cool waters up
with the higher nutrient levels

59:13.875 --> 59:17.163
that can actually restore
conditions for the seaweeds.

59:18.917 --> 59:20.908
Between Australia
and the United States,

59:20.917 --> 59:24.535
there's 100,000,000 km?
Of ocean desert

59:24.542 --> 59:27.409
that is amenable to
marine permaculture.

59:28.500 --> 59:31.788
We can actually restore life
in subtropical oceans,

59:31.792 --> 59:35.785
restore the fish habitat that's
needed to restore fisheries.

59:38.000 --> 59:41.618
Damon: Marine permaculture
is a regenerative technology

59:41.625 --> 59:43.115
that works like this.

59:44.375 --> 59:46.991
A frame made of
recycled material

59:47.000 --> 59:49.992
becomes a platform for
the seaweed to grow on.

59:50.000 --> 59:52.241
It sits just below the surface

59:52.250 --> 59:55.742
and sinks lower as the
seaweed grows and gets heavier.

59:58.125 --> 01:00:01.663
A pump powered simply by
the rise and fall of the ocean,

01:00:01.667 --> 01:00:04.784
brings the cold, nutrient-laden
waters from below

01:00:04.792 --> 01:00:07.374
and disperses them
over the seaweed

01:00:07.375 --> 01:00:09.536
in the upper warmer layer.

01:00:09.542 --> 01:00:11.908
The seaweed can be
regularly harvested

01:00:11.917 --> 01:00:13.999
and used for a range
of purposes.

01:00:15.375 --> 01:00:19.288
Seaweed is good for food,
animal feed, fertiliser,

01:00:19.292 --> 01:00:20.873
fibre and biofuel.

01:00:20.875 --> 01:00:22.911
There's so much we can do
with seaweeds.

01:00:30.542 --> 01:00:36.162
So, we're cruising along in
this very low-carbon vessel,

01:00:36.167 --> 01:00:37.907
following Brian,

01:00:37.917 --> 01:00:40.408
who's swum down
to get the seaweed

01:00:40.417 --> 01:00:42.783
in one of his testing sites
here.

01:00:47.667 --> 01:00:49.248
Except he's gone,

01:00:49.250 --> 01:00:52.492
and he's been underwater for
about two minutes and, um...

01:00:52.500 --> 01:00:53.785
Brian!

01:00:55.792 --> 01:00:57.657
Brian?!

01:00:57.667 --> 01:00:59.498
- Brian: I found it.
- You found it.

01:00:59.500 --> 01:01:01.365
- Yeah.
- Alright, we'll come to you.

01:01:03.042 --> 01:01:04.532
The permaculture tests

01:01:04.542 --> 01:01:08.034
that Brian and his team have
conducted in the south pacific

01:01:08.042 --> 01:01:10.624
have seen marine life return,

01:01:10.625 --> 01:01:14.368
and the seaweed transform the
quality of the water itself.

01:01:17.500 --> 01:01:19.786
Brian: Seaweeds actually
draw down

01:01:19.792 --> 01:01:22.499
carbon dioxide
from the ocean waters.

01:01:23.875 --> 01:01:26.491
And they restore the alkalinity
of the ocean.

01:01:27.792 --> 01:01:31.535
That enables shellfish
and other creatures to thrive.

01:01:35.542 --> 01:01:38.284
Damon, I thought we'd try
some seaweed salad today.

01:01:38.292 --> 01:01:39.782
Oh.

01:01:42.792 --> 01:01:44.623
Well, the little bursts of gas
are good.

01:01:44.625 --> 01:01:46.115
Yeah. Like little poppers.

01:01:49.167 --> 01:01:51.158
Ok. That's actually pretty good.

01:01:51.167 --> 01:01:52.748
Seaweed salad.

01:01:52.750 --> 01:01:55.287
So, what kind of... we're
getting omega 3s in here.

01:01:55.292 --> 01:01:56.532
- What kind of...
- Oh, yeah.

01:01:56.542 --> 01:01:57.873
What's our source?

01:01:57.875 --> 01:02:00.662
Epa, dha, antioxidants,
phytonutrients,

01:02:00.667 --> 01:02:02.282
omega nutrients.

01:02:03.625 --> 01:02:08.369
Damon: But this humble weed has
one more heroic trait to offer.

01:02:09.542 --> 01:02:13.034
It could play a profound role
in drawing down carbon.

01:02:14.250 --> 01:02:16.161
Well, this is an example
of brown seaweed.

01:02:16.167 --> 01:02:20.285
The fastest brown seaweeds
will grow half a metre per day.

01:02:20.292 --> 01:02:22.533
Hang on. Half a metre a day?

01:02:22.542 --> 01:02:24.032
Half a metre a day.

01:02:24.042 --> 01:02:25.907
And they'll grow over 50m long.

01:02:25.917 --> 01:02:28.408
Is that one of the fastest
growing plants in the world?

01:02:28.417 --> 01:02:31.284
It is the fastest-growing
tree on the planet.

01:02:31.292 --> 01:02:33.533
Wow. Ok. So that's why
the understanding of...

01:02:33.542 --> 01:02:35.624
That it's going to be pulling
carbon out of the atmosphere

01:02:35.625 --> 01:02:37.616
very quickly,
because it grows so fast.

01:02:37.625 --> 01:02:41.994
Thousands of tonnes of carbon
per square kilometre per year.

01:02:43.417 --> 01:02:44.782
Wow. Ok.

01:02:46.042 --> 01:02:47.873
Win! It's not a weed at all.

01:02:47.875 --> 01:02:50.912
It's food,
it's habitat for fish,

01:02:50.917 --> 01:02:52.999
it gives back to
the fish ecosystems,

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:54.490
and we balance carbon.

01:02:54.500 --> 01:02:56.036
We measure the carbon export.

01:02:58.792 --> 01:03:01.624
The testing of large-scale
marine permaculture

01:03:01.625 --> 01:03:03.035
is yet to be done.

01:03:04.500 --> 01:03:06.491
But the stakes
couldn't be any higher

01:03:06.500 --> 01:03:07.990
for getting them underway.

01:03:09.792 --> 01:03:15.287
This is all about restoring the
foundation of our civilisation,

01:03:15.292 --> 01:03:17.624
because with climate disruption,

01:03:17.625 --> 01:03:20.287
we'll deplete the soils,
we'll deplete the oceans.

01:03:20.292 --> 01:03:22.408
There will be
no civilisation left

01:03:22.417 --> 01:03:26.035
because any time
you lose that foundation

01:03:26.042 --> 01:03:28.249
of food and the soils
and the seas,

01:03:28.250 --> 01:03:29.990
you lose civilisation as well.

01:03:55.625 --> 01:03:59.789
Damon: So, velvet, because
the warming will increase

01:03:59.792 --> 01:04:02.408
over the next two decades,

01:04:02.417 --> 01:04:05.159
and sea levels
will continue to rise...

01:04:06.500 --> 01:04:12.621
Some countries will need to
adapt in new and creative ways.

01:04:19.917 --> 01:04:22.659
But if predictions of severe
droughts are realised

01:04:22.667 --> 01:04:25.784
that see shortages of food,

01:04:25.792 --> 01:04:29.410
the potential for unprecedented
numbers of refugees

01:04:29.417 --> 01:04:31.783
and civil unrest
around the world...

01:04:33.375 --> 01:04:34.865
Is enormous.

01:04:42.375 --> 01:04:46.288
Just imagine large-scale
marine permaculture,

01:04:46.292 --> 01:04:48.908
helping to mitigate
the severity of such a crisis.

01:04:52.042 --> 01:04:53.907
It could provide
an alternative food source

01:04:53.917 --> 01:04:55.407
to the damaged land crops...

01:04:57.250 --> 01:04:59.787
That is rich in protein
and other nutrients.

01:05:03.042 --> 01:05:04.532
Kate: Instead of having
governments

01:05:04.542 --> 01:05:06.407
that are reacting to disaster,

01:05:06.417 --> 01:05:08.282
we need governments
and communities

01:05:08.292 --> 01:05:11.489
and businesses that proactively
set a new vision

01:05:11.500 --> 01:05:13.365
that prevents these disasters,

01:05:13.375 --> 01:05:15.415
that actually takes us
off in a different direction.

01:05:18.167 --> 01:05:21.534
Investment in marine
permaculture around the world

01:05:21.542 --> 01:05:24.284
could generate countless jobs

01:05:24.292 --> 01:05:26.908
and help us reduce
our meat consumption,

01:05:26.917 --> 01:05:29.624
while sequestering staggering
amounts of carbon.

01:05:33.542 --> 01:05:38.411
Imagine decommissioned oil rigs
converted to house the workers

01:05:38.417 --> 01:05:41.409
and becoming exciting
tourist destinations

01:05:41.417 --> 01:05:44.250
for those keen
to explore marine life.

01:05:52.792 --> 01:05:55.158
The seaweed could be
particularly valuable

01:05:55.167 --> 01:05:59.911
in climate vulnerable areas
like the bay of bengal,

01:05:59.917 --> 01:06:03.614
where it could provide food,
fertiliser and biofuel.

01:06:05.042 --> 01:06:08.660
Along the coast of Africa, it
could provide similar benefits,

01:06:08.667 --> 01:06:11.374
contributing to a thriving
local economy.

01:06:17.167 --> 01:06:19.909
Paul: With mechanisms,
simple ones,

01:06:19.917 --> 01:06:23.284
you are in fact
regenerating the oceans.

01:06:26.250 --> 01:06:27.911
You could feed 10 billion people

01:06:27.917 --> 01:06:30.659
with the protein from
marine permaculture alone.

01:06:50.917 --> 01:06:52.623
At this point of the trip,

01:06:52.625 --> 01:06:56.538
I felt for the first time
like we genuinely have a chance

01:06:56.542 --> 01:06:58.032
at a better future...

01:06:59.125 --> 01:07:00.786
If we choose to take it.

01:07:06.292 --> 01:07:10.410
But before heading home, there
was another subject to address.

01:07:14.542 --> 01:07:17.158
Well, I wish they'd stop
killing off animals

01:07:17.167 --> 01:07:19.658
and, well, forests and whatnot.

01:07:21.250 --> 01:07:22.740
That'd be cool.

01:07:23.750 --> 01:07:27.789
Probably for people to
acknowledge that, like,

01:07:27.792 --> 01:07:29.498
the factories we build

01:07:29.500 --> 01:07:32.913
and, like, they hurt nature
sometimes.

01:07:32.917 --> 01:07:35.033
Like, the things
that we produce,

01:07:35.042 --> 01:07:39.661
it can, like, hurt the wildlife
and it's not good.

01:07:39.667 --> 01:07:41.783
But people just ignore it
right now.

01:07:41.792 --> 01:07:45.660
I would like to see everyone
using the three rs -

01:07:45.667 --> 01:07:48.158
reduce, reuse and recycle.

01:07:48.167 --> 01:07:51.534
Many people know about it,
but don't practice it today.

01:08:03.542 --> 01:08:05.999
Kate: Today's economy, right?

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:07.786
It gets bigger
faster and faster.

01:08:07.792 --> 01:08:11.410
So the economy is doubling
in size nearly every 20 years.

01:08:13.292 --> 01:08:16.613
We take earth's materials,
turn them into stuff we want,

01:08:16.625 --> 01:08:18.832
we use it for a while
and then throw it away.

01:08:18.832 --> 01:08:19.822
Yep.

01:08:19.832 --> 01:08:21.368
And that take, make, use, lose -

01:08:21.375 --> 01:08:23.741
it cuts against the
living cycles of the planet,

01:08:23.750 --> 01:08:26.822
causing climate change,
causing pollution.

01:08:29.875 --> 01:08:32.366
So we're kicking ourselves
out of planetary balance.

01:08:36.207 --> 01:08:38.493
It is difficult to see
the impacts

01:08:38.500 --> 01:08:41.617
of our individual resource use
on the broader environment.

01:08:44.375 --> 01:08:48.072
But our survival could depend
on us making that connection.

01:08:50.625 --> 01:08:54.493
For greater than
99.9% of our evolution,

01:08:54.500 --> 01:08:57.492
human beings lived in this
very intimate association

01:08:57.500 --> 01:08:59.331
with the natural world.

01:08:59.332 --> 01:09:03.076
The decisions we made
on a daily basis as individuals

01:09:03.082 --> 01:09:05.243
within the context of
communities,

01:09:05.250 --> 01:09:07.582
they were informed by
this immediate feedback

01:09:07.582 --> 01:09:09.868
we got from the world around us.

01:09:09.875 --> 01:09:13.367
From the sun, from the water
that was falling on us.

01:09:13.375 --> 01:09:15.741
And you fast forward
to this little blip of time

01:09:15.750 --> 01:09:18.366
that we're in right now,
and, you know,

01:09:18.375 --> 01:09:20.616
we're completely and totally
alienated from nature.

01:09:20.625 --> 01:09:22.115
We've lost that connection.

01:09:25.750 --> 01:09:28.617
I've come to the town of
oberlin in Ohio,

01:09:28.625 --> 01:09:30.240
where John and his team

01:09:30.250 --> 01:09:32.616
have come up with
a quite brilliant way

01:09:32.625 --> 01:09:36.072
to raise awareness of
their community's resource use.

01:09:39.082 --> 01:09:40.823
The environmental dashboard

01:09:40.832 --> 01:09:42.743
was really kind of built around
the science

01:09:42.750 --> 01:09:44.866
and putting people and humans
in connection with

01:09:44.875 --> 01:09:46.991
how they're using
their natural resources.

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:48.740
And so what this does

01:09:48.750 --> 01:09:52.993
is it gives a visual
representation of the usage.

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:55.491
And they put it into the schools

01:09:55.500 --> 01:09:58.367
and so it's really gotten
a lot more into the community.

01:09:58.375 --> 01:10:02.368
And the teachers are
utilising it in their lessons.

01:10:02.375 --> 01:10:04.081
I want you to pay
close attention

01:10:04.083 --> 01:10:06.495
to the squirrel on
the right side.

01:10:06.500 --> 01:10:08.240
And watch what happens.

01:10:08.250 --> 01:10:13.825
As it goes down, he gets sadder
and sadder and starts to cry.

01:10:13.833 --> 01:10:16.245
Teacher: Why do you think the
squirrel got happier or sadder?

01:10:16.250 --> 01:10:17.740
I noticed that too.

01:10:17.750 --> 01:10:19.240
Well, probably
because we're using

01:10:19.250 --> 01:10:21.115
a lot of electricity
at that point.

01:10:21.125 --> 01:10:23.081
More than we regularly used.

01:10:23.083 --> 01:10:24.573
John: We did a controlled study

01:10:24.583 --> 01:10:26.574
where we have
another school system

01:10:26.583 --> 01:10:28.699
very similar to oberlin's
school systems

01:10:28.708 --> 01:10:30.244
in a different area of Ohio.

01:10:30.250 --> 01:10:32.366
They've got
the same curriculum as we do,

01:10:32.375 --> 01:10:33.865
but they don't have dashboard.

01:10:33.875 --> 01:10:36.742
We found as a result of
exposure,

01:10:36.750 --> 01:10:39.617
if you ask them about
electricity use,

01:10:39.625 --> 01:10:42.367
they start talking about
emotions.

01:10:42.375 --> 01:10:44.991
And when you compare
students in our school

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:46.581
with this other school,

01:10:46.583 --> 01:10:48.824
they also have more of
a community response

01:10:48.833 --> 01:10:52.121
when they talk about what needs
to be done about energy use.

01:10:52.125 --> 01:10:53.990
They use the word 'we'.

01:10:54.000 --> 01:10:57.242
And in the other school system,
they use the word 't'.

01:10:57.250 --> 01:10:59.366
So we've seen real change

01:10:59.375 --> 01:11:03.323
as a result of this technology
in the school.

01:11:06.750 --> 01:11:09.822
Damon: What is most exciting
about this idea

01:11:09.833 --> 01:11:11.869
is that the dashboards
could reconnect us

01:11:11.875 --> 01:11:13.456
to a range of resources...

01:11:15.250 --> 01:11:17.115
And influence our behaviour.

01:11:20.625 --> 01:11:22.581
Sharon: It's a way to really
engage the community

01:11:22.583 --> 01:11:24.119
in this discussion,

01:11:24.125 --> 01:11:27.868
regardless of what race,
what education, economic level,

01:11:27.875 --> 01:11:29.740
in this discussion
on sustainability

01:11:29.750 --> 01:11:31.240
and the environment.

01:11:36.958 --> 01:11:39.370
But awareness of
our resource use

01:11:39.375 --> 01:11:41.741
is just one piece of
a complicated puzzle.

01:11:43.333 --> 01:11:44.823
Another solution

01:11:44.833 --> 01:11:47.370
that could have a huge impact
on our dilemma

01:11:47.375 --> 01:11:49.991
caught me completely off-guard.

01:11:53.333 --> 01:11:57.622
Paul: Probably our biggest
surprise was educating girls

01:11:57.625 --> 01:12:00.241
and family planning.

01:12:00.250 --> 01:12:01.865
You combine these two together,

01:12:01.875 --> 01:12:04.366
the number one solution
to reversing global warming

01:12:04.375 --> 01:12:06.206
is the empowerment
of girls and women.

01:12:06.208 --> 01:12:07.698
Damon: Wow.

01:12:15.250 --> 01:12:18.947
Damon: So, our daughter
starts school next year

01:12:18.958 --> 01:12:21.370
and as an Australian,

01:12:21.375 --> 01:12:24.117
I completely take for granted

01:12:24.125 --> 01:12:27.572
that she will get to complete
her education.

01:12:27.583 --> 01:12:29.574
And what I'm just learning here

01:12:29.583 --> 01:12:33.075
is that there are 65 million
girls around the world

01:12:33.083 --> 01:12:34.619
that don't get that opportunity.

01:12:35.833 --> 01:12:37.323
And there's a host of reasons
for that.

01:12:37.333 --> 01:12:39.870
Some are put to work to
support families

01:12:39.875 --> 01:12:41.365
or they're married off.

01:12:41.375 --> 01:12:42.865
But on average,

01:12:42.875 --> 01:12:45.833
those girls will have
five or more children.

01:12:48.583 --> 01:12:50.244
Woman: So we found
that across the board,

01:12:50.250 --> 01:12:51.740
and this isn't just countries

01:12:51.750 --> 01:12:53.240
where there might be
high rates of poverty.

01:12:53.250 --> 01:12:54.615
Even wealthier countries,

01:12:54.625 --> 01:12:57.617
we know that when girls
stay in school for longer

01:12:57.625 --> 01:13:00.742
and they have access to good
reproductive health services,

01:13:00.750 --> 01:13:03.332
as well as decent
work opportunities,

01:13:03.333 --> 01:13:05.995
that women will tend to delay
having children

01:13:06.000 --> 01:13:07.490
until they're ready,

01:13:07.500 --> 01:13:09.957
and then they choose to have
fewer children from then on.

01:13:09.958 --> 01:13:11.619
So, what this does
as a collective,

01:13:11.625 --> 01:13:14.332
is it slows down
the population growth rate,

01:13:14.333 --> 01:13:15.869
which means that
there's less pressure

01:13:15.875 --> 01:13:19.072
and competition for access to
a whole range of resources,

01:13:19.083 --> 01:13:21.244
whether it's food or water
or land.

01:13:22.875 --> 01:13:24.957
Their children tend to
stay in school longer as well

01:13:24.958 --> 01:13:28.746
and, over time, they break
that cycle of poverty.

01:13:32.875 --> 01:13:34.957
So it's a form of
family planning,

01:13:34.958 --> 01:13:36.494
but it's not coercive.

01:13:36.500 --> 01:13:37.956
It's not control.

01:13:37.958 --> 01:13:41.871
It's just empowering girls
